    {
      "step_id": "b67d8985",
      "step_index": 4,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "hERG blockers often follow a \u201c**cation + hydrophobes/aromatics**\u201d pattern:\n- The **protonated amine** can form electrostatic interactions / H-bonding with polar residues in/near the inner cavity and helps \u201canchor\u201d the ligand.\n- The **two phenyl rings** provide strong **hydrophobic and \u03c0\u2013\u03c0 interactions** with aromatic residues in the hERG cavity (classically involving Tyr/Phe residues such as Y652/F656), which is a major driver of potency.\n- The scaffold is **compact but bulky**, likely matching the **cavity-filling** behavior typical of many hERG blockers; the diaryl group can occupy hydrophobic pockets while the cation sits in a favorable position.",
      "tool_name": null,
