    },
    {
      "step_id": "38fc451b",
      "step_index": 6,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "- hERG blockade typically occurs by **binding in the central cavity** accessible from the cytosol in the open/inactivated state.\n- This molecule is expected to be **predominantly cationic**, promoting **entry/retention** in the channel vestibule and enabling strong binding.\n- The **diaryl group** can engage **\u03c0-stacking / hydrophobic contacts** with key aromatic residues lining the pore cavity; the **piperidine N** provides the canonical **basic anchoring point**.\n- The **tert\u2011butyl** on nitrogen increases lipophilicity and steric bulk; it may reduce H-bond donor capacity (already none) but generally **does not remove cationic character**, and can increase membrane partitioning\u2014often correlated with hERG risk.",
      "tool_name": null,
